-- Module 1: The Superpower Stack
INSERT INTO lessons (id, module_id, title, slug, "order", content_type, content, video_url, duration_minutes) VALUES
('11111001-0000-0000-0000-000000000001', '11110001-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
 'Why Claude Code Alone Isn''t Enough', 'why-claude-code-alone-isnt-enough', 1, 'text',
 E'# Why Claude Code Alone Isn''t Enough\n\nClaude Code is the most capable AI coding agent available today. It can read your codebase, write code, run tests, commit, and even push to production. So why would you need anything else?\n\nBecause **capability without structure is chaos.**\n\n## The Four Problems\n\nOut of the box, Claude Code has four critical gaps:\n\n### 1. Stale Knowledge\nClaude''s training data has a cutoff. When you ask it to use the latest Next.js 16 API, it might generate code for Next.js 14. When you ask about a library that released a breaking change last month, it hallucinates the old API. You need **Context7** — real-time documentation injection.\n\n### 2. No Eyes\nClaude Code can write frontend code all day, but it can''t see what it looks like in the browser. It can''t check if a button is misaligned, if a network request failed, or if the page loads slowly. You need **Chrome DevTools MCP** — browser automation and debugging.\n\n### 3. No Structure\nWithout a specification, Claude Code is guessing what you want. It interprets your prompt, makes assumptions, and builds something that might not match your intent. You need **OpenSpec** — a spec-first workflow that aligns human and AI before any code is written.\n\n### 4. No Discipline\nClaude Code will happily skip tests, write code before understanding the problem, and declare success without verification. You need **Superpowers** — a structured workflow plugin that enforces brainstorming, planning, TDD, code review, and proper finishing.\n\n## The Superpower Stack\n\n| Tool | Superpower | Problem Solved |\n|------|-----------|---------------|\n| Context7 | Real-time docs | Stale knowledge / hallucinated APIs |\n| Chrome DevTools MCP | Browser control | Can''t see the UI / no debugging |\n| OpenSpec | Spec-first workflow | Building the wrong thing |\n| Superpowers | Structured discipline | Skipping steps / no TDD |\n\nThese four tools don''t just add features — they transform Claude Code from a chatbot that writes code into an **autonomous engineering system** that follows a professional software development process.\n\n## What You''ll Build\n\nBy the end of this course, you''ll take a project from a one-sentence idea to a deployed, tested, documented application using all four tools working together. No manual coding. No guessing. No stale docs. No invisible bugs.\n\nLet''s install your superpowers.',
 NULL, 8),

('11111002-0000-0000-0000-000000000001', '11110001-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
 'Installing Your Superpowers', 'installing-your-superpowers', 2, 'text',
 E'# Installing Your Superpowers\n\nLet''s get all four tools installed and verified in under 10 minutes.\n\n## Prerequisites\n\n- Claude Code installed (`npm install -g @anthropic-ai/claude-code`)\n- Node.js 18+ and Python 3.10+\n- A Chromium-based browser (Chrome, Edge, Brave)\n- A project directory to work in\n\n## 1. Context7\n\nOne command:\n\n```bash\nnpx ctx7 setup --claude\n```\n\nThis runs OAuth authentication, generates an API key, and installs the MCP server. Verify it works:\n\n```\n> How do I create a middleware in Next.js 16? use context7\n```\n\nIf Claude responds with current Next.js 16 docs instead of outdated patterns, you''re set.\n\n**Optional: Auto-trigger in CLAUDE.md**\n\nAdd this to your project''s `CLAUDE.md` so Context7 activates automatically:\n\n```markdown\nAlways use Context7 to fetch current documentation when working with libraries, frameworks, or APIs.\n```\n\n## 2. Chrome DevTools MCP\n\nInstall as a Claude Code plugin:\n\n```bash\nclaude mcp add chrome-devtools --scope user npx chrome-devtools-mcp@latest\n```\n\nOr install as a plugin from the command palette:\n- Open Claude Code → Command Palette → "Chat: Install Plugin From Source"\n- Enter: `https://github.com/ChromeDevTools/chrome-devtools-mcp`\n\nVerify:\n\n```\n> Navigate to https://example.com and take a screenshot\n```\n\nYou should see Claude open a browser, navigate, and return a screenshot.\n\n## 3. OpenSpec\n\nInstall globally:\n\n```bash\nnpm install -g @fission-ai/openspec\n```\n\nInitialize in your project:\n\n```bash\ncd your-project\nopenspec init\n```\n\nThis creates a `.openspec/` directory with the workflow configuration. Verify:\n\n```\n> /opsx:propose Add a dark mode toggle to the settings page\n```\n\nClaude should create a `changes/` folder with `proposal.md`, `specs/`, `design.md`, and `tasks.md`.\n\n## 4. Superpowers\n\nInstall as a Claude Code plugin:\n\n```bash\nclaude plugin install superpowers\n```\n\nOr from the marketplace: search "Superpowers" in the Claude Code plugin browser.\n\nVerify:\n\n```\n> Let''s brainstorm a new feature for user authentication\n```\n\nSuperpowers should activate automatically, asking clarifying questions and producing a structured design document — not jumping straight to code.\n\n## The Stack is Live\n\nYou now have:\n- **Context7** → up-to-date docs for any library\n- **Chrome DevTools MCP** → browser eyes and hands\n- **OpenSpec** → spec-first artifact workflow\n- **Superpowers** → structured development discipline\n\nIn the next module, we''ll deep-dive into Context7 — the foundation that makes everything else work better.',
 NULL, 10),

-- Module 2: Context7
('11111003-0000-0000-0000-000000000001', '11110002-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
 'Setup & Your First Documentation Query', 'context7-setup-first-query', 1, 'text',
 E'# Context7: Setup & Your First Documentation Query\n\nContext7 solves the single biggest frustration in AI-assisted development: **hallucinated APIs**.\n\nYou ask Claude to use Supabase''s new RPC function, and it generates code using an API that doesn''t exist. You ask for the latest Tailwind CSS class, and it gives you one from v3 when you''re on v4. You waste 30 minutes debugging code that was wrong from the start.\n\nContext7 fixes this by injecting the actual, current documentation into your agent''s context window — in real time.\n\n## How It Works\n\nContext7 maintains an index of library documentation. When you ask a question, it:\n\n1. **Resolves** the library name to a Context7 ID\n2. **Fetches** the relevant documentation pages\n3. **Injects** the content into your agent''s context\n4. Your agent responds using **actual, current APIs**\n\n## Two Modes of Operation\n\n### Mode 1: Explicit Trigger\n\nAppend "use context7" to any prompt:\n\n```\nCreate a Supabase Edge Function that validates a JWT. use context7\n```\n\nContext7 resolves "Supabase", fetches the Edge Functions docs, and Claude writes code using the real API.\n\n### Mode 2: Auto-Trigger (Recommended)\n\nAdd to your `CLAUDE.md`:\n\n```markdown\nUse Context7 to fetch current documentation whenever working with libraries, frameworks, SDKs, APIs, CLI tools, or cloud services.\n```\n\nNow every library question automatically gets real docs — no manual trigger needed.\n\n## Your First Query\n\nLet''s test it with something that changes frequently:\n\n```\nHow do I set up middleware in Next.js 16? use context7\n```\n\n**Without Context7**, Claude might generate:\n```typescript\n// Next.js 14 pattern — WRONG for v16\nexport function middleware(request: NextRequest) {\n  return NextResponse.next()\n}\n```\n\n**With Context7**, Claude fetches the current Next.js 16 docs and generates the correct pattern, including any breaking changes from the version you''re actually using.\n\n## Specifying Libraries\n\nFor ambiguous library names, use the slash syntax:\n\n```\nShow me how to use /supabase/supabase-js to create a real-time subscription. use context7\n```\n\nOr search first:\n\n```bash\nnpx ctx7 library search supabase\n```\n\nThis returns all matching Context7 library IDs.\n\n## What Context7 Covers\n\nContext7 indexes documentation for thousands of libraries including:\n- Frameworks: Next.js, React, Vue, Svelte, Django, Rails\n- Databases: Supabase, Prisma, Drizzle, MongoDB\n- AI: Anthropic SDK, OpenAI, LangChain, CrewAI\n- Infrastructure: Vercel, AWS, Docker, Kubernetes\n- And many more — community-contributed and regularly updated\n\n## The Impact\n\nWith Context7 active, you eliminate an entire class of errors — the ones caused by your agent''s stale training data. Every API call, every configuration option, every CLI flag is verified against the source before your agent writes a single line of code.\n\nThis is the foundation. In the next lesson, we''ll go deeper into advanced patterns.',
 NULL, 10),

('11111004-0000-0000-0000-000000000001', '11110002-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
 'Advanced Context7 — Custom Libraries & Auto-Rules', 'context7-advanced', 2, 'text',
 E'# Advanced Context7 — Custom Libraries & Auto-Rules\n\nNow that Context7 is working, let''s make it invisible — documentation should flow into your agent''s context without you thinking about it.\n\n## CLAUDE.md Auto-Rules\n\nThe most powerful Context7 pattern is setting up rules that trigger automatically based on context. Add these to your project''s `CLAUDE.md`:\n\n```markdown\n# Documentation Rules\n\nUse Context7 to fetch current documentation whenever:\n- Working with any library, framework, SDK, or API\n- Debugging errors related to third-party packages\n- Writing configuration files (tsconfig, vite.config, next.config)\n- Using CLI tools (Supabase CLI, Vercel CLI, Docker)\n\nPrefer Context7 over web search for library docs.\n```\n\nNow when you say "add Stripe checkout to the billing page", Claude automatically fetches the latest Stripe SDK docs — you never type "use context7" again.\n\n## Version-Specific Queries\n\nContext7 can fetch docs for specific versions:\n\n```\nHow does the App Router work in Next.js 16? use context7\n```\n\nVs:\n\n```\nHow does routing work in Next.js 14? use context7\n```\n\nSame library, different versions, different answers — all from the actual docs.\n\n## Combining Context7 with Other Superpowers\n\nContext7 becomes even more powerful when combined with the other tools in this course:\n\n### Context7 + OpenSpec\nWhen writing a spec for a feature that uses a library, Context7 ensures the spec references real APIs:\n\n```\n/opsx:propose Add Stripe subscription management. use context7\n```\n\nThe proposal and design documents will reference actual Stripe API methods, not hallucinated ones.\n\n### Context7 + Superpowers\nDuring the Superpowers planning phase, Context7 grounds every implementation step in reality:\n\n```\nLet''s brainstorm adding real-time features with Supabase. use context7\n```\n\nThe brainstorm document will use Supabase''s actual real-time API, not a made-up one.\n\n### Context7 + Chrome DevTools MCP\nWhen debugging a frontend issue, Context7 provides the correct framework docs while Chrome DevTools shows the actual browser state:\n\n```\nThe Tailwind classes aren''t applying. Check the browser and fix it. use context7\n```\n\nChrome DevTools takes a screenshot, Context7 fetches Tailwind v4 docs, and Claude fixes the issue using the correct class names.\n\n## Troubleshooting\n\n### "Library not found"\nSearch for the exact name: `npx ctx7 library search <name>`\n\n### Rate limits\nGet a free API key from context7.com/dashboard for higher limits.\n\n### Stale results\nContext7 docs are community-maintained. If you find outdated content, you can contribute updates.\n\n## Key Takeaway\n\nContext7 is the foundation of the superpower stack because it eliminates hallucination at the source. Every other tool works better when your agent starts with correct information. Set up the auto-rules, forget about it, and never debug a hallucinated API again.',
 NULL, 10),

-- Module 3: Chrome DevTools MCP
('11111005-0000-0000-0000-000000000001', '11110003-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
 'Setup & Browser Automation Basics', 'chrome-devtools-setup-basics', 1, 'text',
 E'# Chrome DevTools MCP: Setup & Browser Automation Basics\n\nClaude Code can write frontend code, but it''s been doing it blind. It writes HTML, CSS, and JavaScript — then you check the browser, see it''s wrong, describe what''s wrong, and Claude tries again. This back-and-forth wastes enormous amounts of time.\n\nChrome DevTools MCP gives Claude eyes and hands in the browser. It can navigate, click, fill forms, take screenshots, and inspect the DOM — all autonomously.\n\n## Installation\n\n```bash\nclaude mcp add chrome-devtools --scope user npx chrome-devtools-mcp@latest\n```\n\n## The 29 Tools\n\nChrome DevTools MCP exposes 29 MCP tools organized into categories:\n\n### Input Tools\n- `click` — Click an element by CSS selector or text content\n- `fill` — Fill form fields\n- `type` — Type text character by character\n- `press_key` — Press keyboard keys (Enter, Tab, Escape)\n- `hover` — Hover over elements\n- `drag` — Drag and drop\n- `upload_file` — Upload files to file inputs\n\n### Navigation Tools\n- `navigate` — Go to a URL\n- `list_pages` — See all open tabs\n- `select_page` — Switch between tabs\n- `close_page` — Close a tab\n- `wait_for` — Wait for an element or network idle\n\n### Debugging Tools\n- `screenshot` — Capture the current page\n- `evaluate` — Run JavaScript in the page\n- `console_messages` — Read console logs and errors\n- `dom_snapshot` — Get a full DOM tree\n- `network_requests` — List all network requests\n- `get_request` — Inspect a specific request/response\n\n### Performance Tools\n- `start_trace` / `stop_trace` — Record performance traces\n- `lighthouse_audit` — Run a full Lighthouse audit\n- `memory_snapshot` — Capture heap snapshots\n\n## Your First Automation\n\nStart your dev server, then ask Claude:\n\n```\nNavigate to http://localhost:3001 and take a screenshot. \nTell me what you see.\n```\n\nClaude will:\n1. Open Chrome\n2. Navigate to your dev server\n3. Take a screenshot\n4. Analyze the screenshot and describe the page\n\n## Practical Example: Testing a Form\n\n```\nNavigate to http://localhost:3001/auth/signup, fill in the form \nwith test data, submit it, and tell me if the signup succeeded.\n```\n\nClaude will:\n1. Navigate to the signup page\n2. Fill in name, email, password fields\n3. Click the submit button\n4. Wait for the response\n5. Take a screenshot of the result\n6. Report success or failure with details\n\n## The Feedback Loop\n\nThe real power is using Chrome DevTools as part of your development loop:\n\n```\nThe hero section looks wrong on mobile. Check it at 375px width \nand fix any issues.\n```\n\nClaude will:\n1. Set viewport to 375px\n2. Take a screenshot\n3. Identify layout issues\n4. Fix the CSS\n5. Refresh and screenshot again\n6. Verify the fix\n\nNo more "describe what you see" — Claude sees it directly.',
 NULL, 12),

('11111006-0000-0000-0000-000000000001', '11110003-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
 'Debugging, Performance Traces & Lighthouse Audits', 'chrome-devtools-debugging-performance', 2, 'text',
 E'# Debugging, Performance Traces & Lighthouse Audits\n\nScreenshots and form filling are useful, but the real superpower is autonomous debugging. Claude can now inspect what''s happening under the hood — network requests, console errors, performance bottlenecks, accessibility issues — without you copying and pasting error messages.\n\n## Network Request Inspection\n\n```\nNavigate to the dashboard page. Check if any API requests are \nfailing and show me the error responses.\n```\n\nClaude will:\n1. Navigate to the page\n2. List all network requests\n3. Filter for failed requests (4xx, 5xx)\n4. Inspect the response bodies\n5. Report the exact errors\n\nThis is incredibly powerful for debugging API issues. Instead of opening DevTools, finding the request, copying the response, and pasting it into Claude — Claude does it all autonomously.\n\n## Console Error Capture\n\n```\nLoad the homepage and check for any console errors or warnings.\n```\n\nClaude captures console messages with source-mapped stack traces — not just "there''s an error" but exactly where it originates in your source code.\n\n## Performance Traces\n\n```\nRecord a performance trace while navigating from the homepage \nto the dashboard. Identify the slowest operations.\n```\n\nClaude will:\n1. Start a Chrome performance trace\n2. Navigate through the pages\n3. Stop the trace\n4. Analyze the timeline\n5. Report the slowest operations with actionable recommendations\n\n## Lighthouse Audits\n\n```\nRun a Lighthouse audit on the homepage and report the scores.\n```\n\nClaude runs a full Lighthouse audit and returns:\n- Performance score\n- Accessibility score\n- Best Practices score\n- SEO score\n- Specific recommendations for improvement\n\n## Device Emulation\n\n```\nCheck how the pricing page looks on an iPhone 14 Pro and \na Galaxy S24.\n```\n\nClaude emulates different devices, takes screenshots, and compares the layouts.\n\n## Real-World Debugging Workflow\n\nHere''s how Chrome DevTools MCP fits into a real debugging session:\n\n1. **User reports a bug**: "The checkout button doesn''t work"\n2. **You tell Claude**: "Navigate to /checkout, click the buy button, and tell me what happens"\n3. **Claude navigates**, clicks the button, checks the console for errors, inspects the network request, and finds: "The POST to /api/stripe/checkout returns a 401 — the session token is expired"\n4. **Claude fixes the code**, refreshes, and verifies the fix works\n\nThe entire debug cycle — reproduce, diagnose, fix, verify — happens autonomously.\n\n## Configuration Tips\n\n### Use `--isolated` for clean testing\n```bash\nclaude mcp add chrome-devtools --scope user -- npx chrome-devtools-mcp@latest --isolated\n```\nThis creates a temporary browser profile for each session — no cached state interfering with tests.\n\n### Connect to your running browser\n```bash\nclaude mcp add chrome-devtools --scope user -- npx chrome-devtools-mcp@latest --browserUrl http://localhost:9222\n```\nAttach to a browser you already have open with your logged-in sessions.\n\n## Key Takeaway\n\nChrome DevTools MCP closes the feedback loop between code and browser. Your agent doesn''t just write code — it verifies that the code works by looking at the actual result. This is the difference between "I think this should work" and "I verified this works."',
 NULL, 12),

-- Module 4: OpenSpec
('11111007-0000-0000-0000-000000000001', '11110004-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
 'Propose, Design, and Plan Before You Build', 'openspec-propose-design-plan', 1, 'text',
 E'# OpenSpec: Propose, Design, and Plan Before You Build\n\nThe biggest source of wasted time in AI-assisted development isn''t bad code — it''s building the wrong thing. You give Claude a prompt, it interprets it, makes assumptions, and builds something. Sometimes it''s exactly what you wanted. Sometimes it''s close. Sometimes it''s completely wrong.\n\nOpenSpec eliminates this by adding a lightweight specification layer between your idea and the code.\n\n## The Problem with Prompt-First Development\n\n```\n> Add user authentication to the app\n```\n\nWhat authentication? Email/password? OAuth? Magic links? What happens after login — redirect to dashboard or stay on the page? What about password reset? Email verification? Rate limiting?\n\nWithout a spec, Claude makes all these decisions for you. Some will match what you wanted. Some won''t. You''ll discover the mismatches after the code is written.\n\n## OpenSpec''s Artifact Workflow\n\nOpenSpec organizes every feature into a **change** with four artifacts:\n\n### 1. Proposal (`proposal.md`)\nThe **why** — what problem are we solving, what''s in scope, what''s out of scope.\n\n### 2. Specs (`specs/`)\nThe **what** — requirements, acceptance criteria, user scenarios.\n\n### 3. Design (`design.md`)\nThe **how** — technical approach, architecture decisions, trade-offs.\n\n### 4. Tasks (`tasks.md`)\nThe **steps** — implementation checklist, ordered and sized.\n\n## Your First Spec\n\n```\n/opsx:propose Add dark mode support with system preference detection \nand manual toggle\n```\n\nClaude creates a `changes/dark-mode/` folder with all four artifacts:\n\n**proposal.md** might include:\n- Problem: Users in dark environments find the UI harsh\n- Scope: System preference detection, manual toggle, persist preference\n- Out of scope: Per-component theme customization\n\n**specs/** might include:\n- User can toggle between light and dark mode\n- System preference is detected on first visit\n- Preference persists across sessions\n- All components render correctly in both modes\n\n**design.md** might include:\n- Use Tailwind''s `dark:` variant\n- Store preference in localStorage\n- `ThemeProvider` context component\n- No flash of wrong theme on load (script in `<head>`)\n\n**tasks.md** might include:\n- [ ] Add ThemeProvider with localStorage persistence\n- [ ] Add dark mode toggle component\n- [ ] Update all components with dark: variants\n- [ ] Add system preference detection\n- [ ] Test both modes across all pages\n\n## Review and Refine\n\nHere''s the key: **you review the spec before any code is written**. You can:\n- Add requirements you forgot\n- Remove scope that''s too ambitious\n- Change the technical approach\n- Reorder tasks\n\nThis takes 5 minutes. Discovering these issues after the code is written takes hours.\n\n## Philosophy: Fluid Over Rigid\n\nOpenSpec is not a waterfall process. You can update any artifact at any time. If you discover during implementation that the design needs to change, update `design.md` and continue. The spec is a living document, not a contract.',
 NULL, 10),

('11111008-0000-0000-0000-000000000001', '11110004-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
 'Apply, Verify, and Archive — The Full Cycle', 'openspec-apply-verify-archive', 2, 'text',
 E'# Apply, Verify, and Archive — The Full Cycle\n\nYou''ve proposed and the spec is approved. Now let''s implement it.\n\n## Apply: Build From the Spec\n\n```\n/opsx:apply\n```\n\nClaude reads the `tasks.md` and implements each task in order. Because the design decisions are already made and the tasks are already scoped, Claude doesn''t need to guess — it follows the plan.\n\nThe difference between `/opsx:apply` and "just build it":\n- Claude knows exactly what to build (from specs)\n- Claude knows how to build it (from design)\n- Claude knows the order (from tasks)\n- Claude knows what''s out of scope (from proposal)\n\n## Verify: Check the Work\n\n```\n/opsx:verify\n```\n\nClaude checks each spec requirement against the implementation:\n- Does the toggle work? ✓\n- Does system preference detection work? ✓\n- Does the preference persist? ✓\n- Do all components render correctly? ✓\n\nIf anything fails, Claude reports what''s missing and can fix it.\n\n## Archive: Clean Up\n\n```\n/opsx:archive\n```\n\nMoves the completed change from `changes/` to `changes/.archive/`. Your workspace stays clean, but the spec history is preserved.\n\n## The Extended Workflow\n\nOpenSpec also provides commands for ongoing work:\n\n### Continue a Paused Change\n```\n/opsx:continue\n```\nResumes work on the current change, picking up where you left off.\n\n### Fast-Forward\n```\n/opsx:ff\n```\nIf you made manual changes that satisfy some tasks, fast-forward marks them complete.\n\n### Sync Spec with Reality\n```\n/opsx:sync\n```\nIf the implementation drifted from the spec, sync updates the artifacts to match what was actually built.\n\n### Onboard to an Existing Project\n```\n/opsx:onboard\n```\nGenerates a project overview for a new codebase, helping Claude understand the architecture before proposing changes.\n\n### Bulk Archive\n```\n/opsx:bulk-archive\n```\nArchive all completed changes at once.\n\n## OpenSpec + Other Superpowers\n\n### OpenSpec + Context7\nSpec references real APIs because Context7 provides current documentation during the propose phase.\n\n### OpenSpec + Superpowers\nSuperpowers'' brainstorming phase can feed into OpenSpec''s proposal. Brainstorm first, then formalize into a spec.\n\n### OpenSpec + Chrome DevTools\nThe verify step can use Chrome DevTools to visually confirm UI specs are met — not just code review, but actual browser verification.\n\n## When to Use OpenSpec\n\n| Situation | Use OpenSpec? |\n|-----------|------|\n| New feature with multiple requirements | Yes |\n| Bug fix with clear steps | No — just fix it |\n| Refactor with defined scope | Yes |\n| Quick one-line change | No |\n| Feature you''ll need to explain to others | Yes |\n\nThe rule: **if you''d regret not having a spec halfway through, write the spec.**\n\n## Key Takeaway\n\nOpenSpec turns AI-assisted development from "prompt and pray" into "propose, approve, build, verify." The 5 minutes you spend reviewing a spec saves hours of rework.',
 NULL, 10),

-- Module 5: Superpowers
('11111009-0000-0000-0000-000000000001', '11110005-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
 'Brainstorming & Planning with Discipline', 'superpowers-brainstorm-plan', 1, 'text',
 E'# Superpowers: Brainstorming & Planning with Discipline\n\nThe Superpowers plugin enforces a structured development workflow that prevents Claude from doing what it naturally wants to do: jump straight to writing code.\n\n## The 7-Stage Workflow\n\n```\n1. Brainstorm  →  Explore the problem space\n2. Worktree    →  Create an isolated workspace\n3. Plan        →  Break work into small, verified tasks\n4. Build       →  Implement with TDD (subagent-driven)\n5. Review      →  Check work against the plan\n6. Test        →  Verify everything passes\n7. Finish      →  Merge, PR, or discard\n```\n\nSuperpowers activates automatically based on context. When you say "let''s build a feature", it starts with brainstorming — not code.\n\n## Stage 1: Brainstorming\n\nWhen you describe a feature, Superpowers forces Claude to:\n\n1. **Ask clarifying questions** — not assume\n2. **Explore alternatives** — not pick the first approach\n3. **Produce a design document** — not a code dump\n4. **Present it in chunks** — not a wall of text\n5. **Wait for approval** — not forge ahead\n\n### Example\n\n```\n> Let''s add real-time notifications to the dashboard\n```\n\nWithout Superpowers, Claude would immediately write a WebSocket implementation.\n\nWith Superpowers, Claude asks:\n- What events should trigger notifications?\n- Should they persist or be ephemeral?\n- Do users need to mark them as read?\n- Should they work across tabs?\n- What''s the notification UI — toast, bell icon, sidebar?\n\nThen it produces a design document covering architecture options (WebSocket vs SSE vs polling), trade-offs, and a recommended approach — all before writing a single line of code.\n\n## Stage 2: Git Worktrees\n\nAfter the design is approved, Superpowers creates a git worktree:\n\n```bash\ngit worktree add .worktrees/notifications -b feat/notifications\n```\n\nThis gives you an isolated workspace on a new branch with a clean test baseline. If anything goes wrong, your main branch is untouched.\n\n## Stage 3: Planning\n\nSuperpowers breaks the approved design into tasks that are:\n\n- **Small** — 2-5 minutes each\n- **Complete** — exact file paths, complete code, not pseudocode\n- **Verified** — each task has a verification step\n- **Ordered** — dependencies are respected\n\n### Plan Principles\n\n| Principle | What It Means |\n|-----------|------|\n| YAGNI | Don''t build what isn''t needed yet |\n| DRY | Don''t repeat yourself |\n| Simplicity | The simplest solution that works |\n| Evidence | Verify before declaring success |\n\nThe plan is the contract. Every task will be implemented exactly as specified — no creative interpretation, no scope creep.\n\n## Key Takeaway\n\nBrainstorming and planning feel slow, but they eliminate the most expensive mistakes — building the wrong thing, building too much, and building without tests. Superpowers enforces the discipline that experienced engineers have and juniors skip.',
 NULL, 12),

('11111010-0000-0000-0000-000000000001', '11110005-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
 'Git Worktrees, Code Review & Finishing', 'superpowers-worktrees-review-finish', 2, 'text',
 E'# Git Worktrees, Code Review & Finishing\n\nThe Superpowers workflow doesn''t end when the code is written. The finishing stages — review, test, and close — are where quality is ensured.\n\n## Code Review Between Tasks\n\nAfter each task is completed, Superpowers runs a two-stage review:\n\n### Stage 1: Spec Compliance\n- Does the implementation match the plan?\n- Are there any deviations from the design?\n- Were any shortcuts taken?\n\n### Stage 2: Code Quality\n- Are there any bugs or edge cases?\n- Is the code clean and maintainable?\n- Are tests comprehensive?\n\nCritical issues block progress — you can''t move to the next task until the review passes. This prevents the "I''ll fix it later" pattern that creates technical debt.\n\n## The Finishing Stage\n\nWhen all tasks are complete and all reviews pass, Superpowers enters the finishing stage:\n\n1. **Verify all tests pass** — run the full test suite\n2. **Present options**:\n   - **Merge** — merge the worktree branch into main\n   - **PR** — create a pull request for team review\n   - **Keep** — keep the worktree for further work\n   - **Discard** — delete the worktree and branch\n3. **Clean up** — remove the worktree directory\n\n## Giving and Receiving Code Reviews\n\nSuperpowers also includes skills for reviewing code from others:\n\n```\n> Review this PR for potential issues\n```\n\nClaude performs a structured review:\n- Security vulnerabilities\n- Logic errors\n- Performance concerns\n- Test coverage gaps\n- Code style consistency\n\n## Systematic Debugging\n\nWhen things go wrong, Superpowers provides a 4-phase debugging skill:\n\n1. **Reproduce** — confirm the bug exists and is consistent\n2. **Isolate** — narrow down the root cause\n3. **Fix** — implement the minimal fix\n4. **Verify** — confirm the fix works and doesn''t break other things\n\nNo guessing, no shotgun debugging, no "let me try something" — a systematic process.\n\n## Writing New Skills\n\nSuperpowers includes a meta-skill for writing new skills:\n\n```\n> Create a new skill for database migration reviews\n```\n\nClaude generates a structured skill definition that integrates into the Superpowers workflow. This is how you customize the system for your team''s needs.\n\n## Key Takeaway\n\nThe Superpowers workflow ensures that every piece of code goes through brainstorming, planning, TDD, review, and proper finishing. It''s the difference between a developer who ships fast and breaks things, and a developer who ships fast and ships quality.',
 NULL, 10),

-- Module 6: Subagent-Driven Development
('11111011-0000-0000-0000-000000000001', '11110006-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
 'Test-Driven Development with AI Agents', 'tdd-with-ai-agents', 1, 'text',
 E'# Test-Driven Development with AI Agents\n\nSuperpowers enforces strict TDD — and it''s not optional. This is the stage where most AI-assisted development goes wrong, and Superpowers is opinionated about getting it right.\n\n## The TDD Mandate\n\nSuperpowers follows strict RED-GREEN-REFACTOR:\n\n### RED: Write a Failing Test\n```\n1. Write a test that describes the desired behavior\n2. Run the test — it MUST fail\n3. If it passes, the test is wrong (it''s testing something that already exists)\n```\n\n### GREEN: Make It Pass\n```\n1. Write the MINIMUM code to make the test pass\n2. No extra features, no "while I''m here" improvements\n3. Run the test — it MUST pass\n```\n\n### REFACTOR: Clean Up\n```\n1. Improve the code without changing behavior\n2. Run the tests — they MUST still pass\n3. Commit\n```\n\n## The Nuclear Rule\n\n> **Code written before tests gets deleted.**\n\nSuperpowers will literally discard code that was written without a corresponding failing test first. This sounds extreme, but it prevents the most common failure mode in AI-assisted development: Claude writes a huge block of code, you accept it, and then discover it doesn''t work. With TDD, you discover issues incrementally.\n\n## Why TDD Matters More with AI\n\nWith human developers, skipping TDD means slower feedback loops and more bugs. With AI agents, skipping TDD means something worse: **false confidence**.\n\nClaude will tell you "Done! I''ve implemented the feature" — and it looks right in the code. But without tests, you have no evidence it works. Tests are the proof.\n\n## TDD in Practice\n\nHere''s how a Superpowers TDD cycle looks:\n\n```\nTask: Add email validation to signup form\n\n1. RED — Claude writes test:\n   test("rejects invalid email formats", () => {\n     expect(validateEmail("not-an-email")).toBe(false)\n   })\n   → Test fails (validateEmail doesn''t exist)\n\n2. GREEN — Claude writes minimal code:\n   function validateEmail(email) {\n     return /^[^@]+@[^@]+\\.[^@]+$/.test(email)\n   }\n   → Test passes\n\n3. REFACTOR — Claude improves:\n   - Adds edge cases to tests\n   - Extracts regex to a constant\n   - Adds TypeScript types\n   → All tests still pass\n\n4. COMMIT\n```\n\nEach cycle takes 2-5 minutes. After 10 cycles, you have a fully tested feature with proof it works.\n\n## Key Takeaway\n\nTDD with AI agents isn''t about testing philosophy — it''s about trust. Tests are the evidence that the AI''s code actually works. Without them, you''re trusting the chatbot. With them, you''re trusting the test suite.',
 NULL, 12),

('11111012-0000-0000-0000-000000000001', '11110006-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
 'Parallel Agents & Multi-Hour Autonomous Sessions', 'parallel-agents-autonomous', 2, 'text',
 E'# Parallel Agents & Multi-Hour Autonomous Sessions\n\nThis is the final boss of Claude Code Superpowers: dispatching multiple AI agents to work on different tasks simultaneously, running autonomously for hours, while maintaining quality through two-stage review.\n\n## Subagent-Driven Development\n\nThe key insight from the Superpowers plugin is that **each task should be handled by a fresh subagent**.\n\nWhy? Because AI agents accumulate context drift. After working on 10 tasks, the agent''s context window is full of old code, old errors, old decisions. A fresh agent starts clean — it reads only the task spec, implements it, and moves on.\n\n## How It Works\n\n1. **Plan phase** produces a list of tasks (2-5 minutes each)\n2. **For each task**, Superpowers spawns a fresh subagent with:\n   - The task specification (from the plan)\n   - The current codebase state\n   - TDD rules (write test first, then code)\n3. **Subagent implements** the task following TDD\n4. **Two-stage review**:\n   - Stage 1: Does it match the spec?\n   - Stage 2: Is the code quality acceptable?\n5. **If review passes**, commit and move to next task\n6. **If review fails**, fix issues and re-review\n\n## Parallel Dispatch\n\nWhen tasks are independent (no dependencies between them), Superpowers can dispatch multiple subagents in parallel:\n\n```\nTasks 1-3: Sequential (each depends on the previous)\nTasks 4-6: Parallel (independent of each other)\nTask 7: Sequential (depends on 4-6)\n```\n\nThis can cut build time by 2-3x for feature work with independent components.\n\n## Multi-Hour Sessions\n\nThe combination of:\n- Small, well-defined tasks (from planning)\n- Fresh subagents (no context drift)\n- Two-stage review (quality gate)\n- TDD (proof of correctness)\n\n...means you can start a build session and walk away. Superpowers will:\n1. Pick up the next task\n2. Spawn a subagent\n3. Implement with TDD\n4. Review the work\n5. Commit if it passes\n6. Move to the next task\n7. Repeat for hours\n\nWhen you come back, you have a working feature with tests, reviews, and clean commits.\n\n## When to Go Autonomous\n\n| Scenario | Autonomous? |\n|----------|------|\n| Well-planned feature with clear tasks | Yes |\n| Exploratory work / unclear requirements | No — stay interactive |\n| Refactoring with comprehensive tests | Yes |\n| Security-critical code | No — review each step |\n| UI work (needs visual verification) | Partially — use Chrome DevTools MCP for verification |\n\n## The Complete Flow\n\n```\nBrainstorm → Approve → Worktree → Plan → \n  [Subagent 1: Task 1 (TDD → Review → Commit)]\n  [Subagent 2: Task 2 (TDD → Review → Commit)]\n  [Subagent 3: Task 3 (TDD → Review → Commit)]\n→ All tests pass → Finish → Merge/PR\n```\n\nThis is what "AI orchestration" looks like in practice — you''re not writing code, you''re directing agents that write, test, and review code for you.\n\n## Key Takeaway\n\nSubagent-driven development is the endgame of AI-assisted coding. You define what to build, the system builds it with discipline and quality. Your job shifts from writing code to reviewing plans and approving results.',
 NULL, 12),

-- Module 7: Full Stack Superpowers
('11111013-0000-0000-0000-000000000001', '11110007-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
 'From Idea to Deployed App Using All Four Tools', 'full-stack-project', 1, 'text',
 E'# From Idea to Deployed App Using All Four Tools\n\nLet''s put it all together. We''ll take a project from a one-sentence idea to a deployed, tested application using every superpower in your toolkit.\n\n## The Project: A Team Standup Bot\n\nA web app where team members post daily standups (what I did, what I''m doing, blockers), and the app generates AI summaries for managers.\n\n## Phase 1: Spec It (OpenSpec)\n\n```\n/opsx:propose Build a team standup web app with AI summaries. \nTeam members post daily updates, managers get AI-generated \nsummary digests. use context7\n```\n\nContext7 kicks in to fetch the latest Next.js, Supabase, and Anthropic SDK docs. OpenSpec creates:\n\n- **proposal.md** — scope, target users, MVP vs future\n- **specs/** — user stories, acceptance criteria\n- **design.md** — tech stack decisions (Next.js + Supabase + Claude API), schema design, component architecture\n- **tasks.md** — ordered implementation steps\n\nYou review, adjust scope, approve.\n\n## Phase 2: Plan It (Superpowers)\n\nSuperpowers takes the approved OpenSpec design and breaks it into 2-5 minute tasks:\n\n```\nTask 1: Initialize Next.js project with Supabase\nTask 2: Create database schema (teams, users, standups)\nTask 3: Build auth flow (signup, login, team join)\nTask 4: Build standup submission form\nTask 5: Build standup list view\nTask 6: Add Claude API summary generation\nTask 7: Build manager dashboard with summaries\nTask 8: Add email digest (Postmark)\nTask 9: Deploy to Vercel\n```\n\nEach task has exact file paths, code specifications, and verification steps.\n\n## Phase 3: Build It (Subagents + TDD)\n\nSuperpowers creates a git worktree and dispatches subagents:\n\n- Tasks 1-3: Sequential (foundation)\n- Tasks 4-5: Parallel (independent UI components)\n- Task 6: Sequential (depends on 4-5)\n- Tasks 7-8: Parallel (independent features)\n- Task 9: Sequential (final)\n\nEach subagent follows TDD: write failing test → implement → refactor → commit.\n\nContext7 ensures every Supabase query, every Next.js route, every Claude API call uses the **current** API — no hallucinated methods.\n\n## Phase 4: Verify It (Chrome DevTools MCP)\n\nAfter the build phase, Chrome DevTools MCP verifies:\n\n```\nNavigate to localhost:3001, create a test account, post a standup, \ncheck the manager dashboard for the AI summary. Screenshot each step.\n```\n\nClaude navigates through the entire user flow, takes screenshots at each step, checks for console errors, verifies the AI summary renders correctly.\n\n## Phase 5: Ship It (Superpowers Finish)\n\nSuperpowers runs all tests, presents the merge/PR option, and cleans up the worktree.\n\n## The Result\n\n- A working app built from a one-sentence idea\n- Every API call uses current documentation (Context7)\n- Every feature has tests (Superpowers TDD)\n- The UI is verified in a real browser (Chrome DevTools)\n- The spec is documented and archived (OpenSpec)\n\nThis is what AI orchestration looks like when you have all four superpowers working together.',
 NULL, 15),

('11111014-0000-0000-0000-000000000001', '11110007-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
 'Your Superpower Toolkit — What to Use When', 'superpower-toolkit-reference', 2, 'text',
 E'# Your Superpower Toolkit — What to Use When\n\nYou now have four powerful tools. The art is knowing which to reach for and when to combine them.\n\n## Quick Reference\n\n| Situation | Tool | Why |\n|-----------|------|-----|\n| Using a library you''re not sure about | Context7 | Get current docs, not hallucinated APIs |\n| Frontend doesn''t look right | Chrome DevTools MCP | Screenshot, inspect, fix, verify |\n| Building a feature with multiple requirements | OpenSpec | Spec before you build |\n| Starting any non-trivial work | Superpowers | Brainstorm → Plan → Build → Review |\n| Debugging an API error | Chrome DevTools MCP | Inspect network requests |\n| Need to check a library''s latest API | Context7 | Resolve + query docs |\n| Want autonomous multi-task builds | Superpowers + subagents | Parallel TDD with review |\n| Need to verify a deploy works | Chrome DevTools MCP | Navigate, test, screenshot |\n\n## Combination Patterns\n\n### The Gold Standard (All Four)\n```\nOpenSpec → Superpowers → Context7 + Chrome DevTools throughout\n```\nUse for: New features, greenfield projects, anything important.\n\n### The Quick Fix (Context7 + Chrome DevTools)\n```\nContext7 for correct API → Fix → Chrome DevTools to verify\n```\nUse for: Bug fixes, small changes, quick patches.\n\n### The Spec Review (OpenSpec + Context7)\n```\nOpenSpec proposal + Context7 docs → Review → Apply\n```\nUse for: Planning features that use unfamiliar libraries.\n\n### The Autonomous Build (Superpowers + Context7)\n```\nSuperpowers plan → Subagent dispatch → Context7 for docs\n```\nUse for: Well-defined work you want to run unattended.\n\n## Anti-Patterns\n\n### Don''t: Use OpenSpec for everything\nA one-line bug fix doesn''t need a proposal, spec, design, and task list. Use judgment.\n\n### Don''t: Skip Context7 because "I know this library"\nYour agent doesn''t know it as well as you do. Let Context7 provide the docs anyway.\n\n### Don''t: Ignore Chrome DevTools verification\n"It should work" is not the same as "I verified it works." Take the screenshot.\n\n### Don''t: Fight the Superpowers workflow\nIf Superpowers asks clarifying questions during brainstorming, answer them. The discipline exists because skipping steps causes rework.\n\n## Your CLAUDE.md Template\n\nAdd this to every project:\n\n```markdown\n# Superpowers\n\n- Always use Context7 for library documentation\n- Use Chrome DevTools MCP to verify UI changes\n- For features with 3+ requirements, use OpenSpec first\n- Follow the Superpowers workflow for all non-trivial work\n- TDD is mandatory — write the failing test first\n```\n\n## What''s Next\n\nYou now have the tools that separate AI-assisted developers who ship fast and break things from those who ship fast and ship quality. The superpower isn''t the AI — it''s the system around the AI.\n\nGo build something.',
 NULL, 10);

-- Module 8: Skills Reference
('11111015-0000-0000-0000-000000000001', '11110008-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
 'Superpowers & OpenSpec — Complete Skills Reference', 'skills-ref-superpowers-openspec', 1, 'text',
 E'# Superpowers & OpenSpec — Complete Skills Reference\n\nThis lesson is your reference card for every skill and command in the Superpowers plugin and OpenSpec framework. Bookmark it.\n\n---\n\n## Superpowers Plugin Skills\n\nSuperpowers skills activate automatically based on context — you don''t invoke them manually. The agent detects what phase of work you''re in and activates the relevant skill.\n\n### Core Workflow Skills (7 stages)\n\n| # | Skill | Trigger | What It Does |\n|---|-------|---------|------|\n| 1 | **Brainstorming** | "Let''s build...", "I want to add..." | Asks clarifying questions, explores alternatives, produces a design document in digestible chunks. Waits for approval before proceeding. |\n| 2 | **Git Worktree** | After brainstorm approval | Creates `git worktree add .worktrees/<name> -b feat/<name>` — isolated workspace on a new branch with clean test baseline. |\n| 3 | **Planning** | After worktree created | Breaks approved design into tasks: 2-5 minutes each, exact file paths, complete code (not pseudocode), verification steps. Enforces YAGNI, DRY, simplicity. |\n| 4 | **Subagent-Driven Development** | During build phase | Spawns a fresh subagent per task. Two-stage review (spec compliance, then code quality). Can run in parallel for independent tasks. |\n| 5 | **Test-Driven Development** | During each task | Enforces strict RED-GREEN-REFACTOR. Code written before tests gets deleted. Every task starts with a failing test. |\n| 6 | **Code Review** | Between tasks | Reviews completed work against the plan. Critical issues block progress. Checks spec compliance and code quality. |\n| 7 | **Finishing** | All tasks complete | Runs full test suite. Presents options: Merge, PR, Keep, Discard. Cleans up worktree. |\n\n### Additional Superpowers Skills\n\n| Skill | When to Use | What It Does |\n|-------|------------|------|\n| **Systematic Debugging** | Bug reports, test failures | 4-phase process: Reproduce → Isolate → Fix → Verify. No guessing. |\n| **Giving Code Reviews** | Reviewing PRs or code | Structured review: security, logic, performance, tests, style. |\n| **Receiving Code Reviews** | Getting feedback | Processes review comments systematically, implements fixes. |\n| **Parallel Dispatch** | Independent tasks | Spawns multiple subagents simultaneously for non-dependent tasks. |\n| **Writing Skills** | Creating custom workflows | Meta-skill: generates new skill definitions that integrate into the workflow. |\n\n### Superpowers Configuration\n\nSuperpowers reads from your project''s `CLAUDE.md` and the plugin''s skill files. You can customize behavior by:\n\n- Adding project-specific rules to `CLAUDE.md`\n- Creating custom skills using the Writing Skills meta-skill\n- Adjusting task size preferences in the planning prompts\n\n---\n\n## OpenSpec Slash Commands\n\nOpenSpec commands are invoked explicitly with the `/opsx:` prefix.\n\n### Core Workflow Commands\n\n| Command | What It Does | Creates/Modifies |\n|---------|-------------|------|\n| `/opsx:propose <feature>` | Creates a change folder with all 4 artifacts | `changes/<name>/proposal.md`, `specs/`, `design.md`, `tasks.md` |\n| `/opsx:apply` | Implements tasks from `tasks.md` in order | Code files, tests |\n| `/opsx:verify` | Checks each spec requirement against implementation | Reports pass/fail per requirement |\n| `/opsx:archive` | Moves completed change to `.archive/` | `changes/.archive/<name>/` |\n\n### Extended Workflow Commands\n\n| Command | What It Does | When to Use |\n|---------|-------------|------|\n| `/opsx:new` | Creates a blank change folder | When you want to write the spec manually |\n| `/opsx:continue` | Resumes work on current change | After a break or context switch |\n| `/opsx:ff` | Fast-forwards past manually completed tasks | When you did some tasks yourself |\n| `/opsx:sync` | Updates spec artifacts to match actual implementation | When implementation drifted from spec |\n| `/opsx:bulk-archive` | Archives all completed changes at once | Cleanup after a sprint |\n| `/opsx:onboard` | Generates project overview | Joining a new codebase |\n\n### OpenSpec Artifacts\n\n| Artifact | Purpose | Contents |\n|----------|---------|------|\n| `proposal.md` | The **why** | Problem statement, scope, out-of-scope, success criteria |\n| `specs/` | The **what** | Requirements, acceptance criteria, user scenarios |\n| `design.md` | The **how** | Technical approach, architecture, trade-offs |\n| `tasks.md` | The **steps** | Ordered, sized implementation checklist |',
 NULL, 12),

('11111016-0000-0000-0000-000000000001', '11110008-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
 'Context7 & Chrome DevTools MCP — Complete Tools Reference', 'skills-ref-context7-devtools', 2, 'text',
 E'# Context7 & Chrome DevTools MCP — Complete Tools Reference\n\nYour reference card for every Context7 command and all 29 Chrome DevTools MCP tools.\n\n---\n\n## Context7 Tools & Commands\n\n### MCP Tools (called by the agent)\n\n| Tool | What It Does | Example |\n|------|-------------|------|\n| `resolve-library-id` | Searches Context7 index for a library, returns its ID | Input: "next.js" → Output: `/vercel/next.js` |\n| `query-docs` | Fetches documentation for a library ID + query | Input: ID `/vercel/next.js`, query "middleware" → Output: Current middleware docs |\n\n### CLI Commands (run in terminal)\n\n| Command | What It Does |\n|---------|------|\n| `npx ctx7 setup` | One-time setup: OAuth, API key, MCP server registration |\n| `npx ctx7 setup --claude` | Setup specifically for Claude Code |\n| `npx ctx7 library search <name>` | Search for a library in the Context7 index |\n| `npx ctx7 docs <library-id> <query>` | Fetch docs from the CLI |\n\n### Trigger Patterns\n\n| Pattern | Example |\n|---------|------|\n| Explicit trigger | "How do I use middleware in Next.js? **use context7**" |\n| Library slash syntax | "Show me **/supabase/supabase-js** real-time subscriptions. use context7" |\n| Auto-trigger (CLAUDE.md rule) | Add: "Always use Context7 for library docs" — no trigger phrase needed |\n\n---\n\n## Chrome DevTools MCP — All 29 Tools\n\n### Input Tools (7)\n\n| Tool | What It Does | Key Parameters |\n|------|-------------|------|\n| `click` | Click an element | `selector` (CSS) or `text` (visible text) |\n| `fill` | Fill a form field | `selector`, `value` |\n| `type` | Type text character by character | `text`, optional `selector` |\n| `press_key` | Press a keyboard key | `key` (Enter, Tab, Escape, etc.) |\n| `hover` | Hover over an element | `selector` |\n| `drag` | Drag and drop | `from` selector, `to` selector |\n| `upload_file` | Upload a file to a file input | `selector`, `path` |\n\n### Navigation Tools (5)\n\n| Tool | What It Does | Key Parameters |\n|------|-------------|------|\n| `navigate` | Go to a URL | `url` |\n| `wait_for` | Wait for an element or network idle | `selector` or `state` |\n| `list_pages` | List all open browser tabs | — |\n| `select_page` | Switch to a specific tab | `page` index |\n| `close_page` | Close a tab | `page` index |\n\n### Emulation Tools (2)\n\n| Tool | What It Does | Key Parameters |\n|------|-------------|------|\n| `emulate_device` | Emulate a specific device | `device` name (e.g. "iPhone 14 Pro") |\n| `resize` | Change viewport dimensions | `width`, `height` |\n\n### Debugging Tools (6)\n\n| Tool | What It Does | Key Parameters |\n|------|-------------|------|\n| `screenshot` | Capture current page as image | `fullPage` (boolean) |\n| `evaluate` | Run JavaScript in the page context | `expression` (JS code) |\n| `console_messages` | Read console logs, warnings, errors | — (returns all messages with stack traces) |\n| `dom_snapshot` | Get full DOM tree | — |\n| `network_requests` | List all network requests | — (returns URL, method, status, timing) |\n| `get_request` | Inspect a specific request + response body | `requestId` |\n\n### Performance Tools (5)\n\n| Tool | What It Does | Key Parameters |\n|------|-------------|------|\n| `start_trace` | Begin recording a performance trace | `categories` (optional) |\n| `stop_trace` | Stop recording, return trace data | — |\n| `analyze_trace` | Extract actionable insights from a trace | `trace` data |\n| `memory_snapshot` | Capture a heap snapshot | — |\n| `lighthouse_audit` | Run a full Lighthouse audit | `categories` (performance, accessibility, etc.) |\n\n### Network Tools (2)\n\n| Tool | What It Does | Key Parameters |\n|------|-------------|------|\n| `network_requests` | List all captured network requests | — |\n| `get_request` | Get full request/response details | `requestId` |\n\n### Configuration Flags\n\n| Flag | What It Does |\n|------|------|\n| `--isolated` | Temporary browser profile, cleaned up after session |\n| `--headless` | Run without visible browser window |\n| `--browserUrl <url>` | Attach to already-running Chrome instance |\n| `--chromePath <path>` | Use a specific Chrome/Chromium binary |\n| `--viewport <WxH>` | Set initial viewport size |\n| `--proxy <url>` | Route traffic through a proxy |\n| `--slim` | Expose only 3 core tools (navigate, screenshot, click) |\n\n---\n\n## Quick Lookup: "I want to…"\n\n| I want to… | Use this tool |\n|------------|------|\n| Check if my page loads correctly | `navigate` + `screenshot` |\n| See why an API call fails | `network_requests` + `get_request` |\n| Find JavaScript errors | `console_messages` |\n| Test a form end-to-end | `navigate` + `fill` + `click` + `screenshot` |\n| Check mobile responsiveness | `emulate_device` + `screenshot` |\n| Measure page performance | `lighthouse_audit` or `start_trace` + `stop_trace` |\n| Debug a slow page | `start_trace` + `analyze_trace` |\n| Get the latest API docs | Context7: `resolve-library-id` + `query-docs` |\n| Verify a deploy works | `navigate` + `click` through flows + `screenshot` |\n| Check accessibility | `lighthouse_audit` with accessibility category |',
 NULL, 12);

